1
00:00:44,077 --> 00:00:46,443
La-la-la

2
00:00:46,513 --> 00:00:50,279
La-la, la-la-la...

3
00:00:52,952 --> 00:00:54,180
You ready?

4
00:00:54,254 --> 00:00:56,119
Oh. Not going.

5
00:00:56,189 --> 00:00:58,316
Not dressing up like an adult.

6
00:00:58,391 --> 00:01:00,359
Yeah, but we're
game-day players.

7
00:01:00,427 --> 00:01:01,519
Come on.

8
00:01:01,594 --> 00:01:03,289
Let's go.

9
00:01:03,363 --> 00:01:06,127
Okay.

10
00:01:06,199 --> 00:01:09,657
l put on the clothes,
and l feel better for a second

11
00:01:09,736 --> 00:01:12,227
like l'm somebody
with someplace to go

12
00:01:12,305 --> 00:01:14,739
but then l think
l'm a complete fraud

13
00:01:14,808 --> 00:01:16,935
and they'll see
right through me.

14
00:01:17,043 --> 00:01:18,635
...La-la-la

15
00:01:18,711 --> 00:01:21,179
La-la, la-la-la...

16
00:01:24,150 --> 00:01:26,277
A fine fantasy object,
but useful, too--

17
00:01:26,352 --> 00:01:29,150
shitting, sitting,
insulation in the winter months.

18
00:01:29,222 --> 00:01:30,883
Sam...

19
00:01:33,626 --> 00:01:36,561
...La-la-la

20
00:01:36,629 --> 00:01:37,755
La-la, la-la-la...

21
00:01:37,831 --> 00:01:39,389
Not an easy job market

22
00:01:39,466 --> 00:01:42,492
but you're the most sought-after
graduates in history.

23
00:01:42,569 --> 00:01:43,695
Know your value.

24
00:01:43,770 --> 00:01:45,294
Sell to the highest bidder.

25
00:01:45,371 --> 00:01:46,463
Now, we know your...

26
00:01:46,539 --> 00:01:48,564
...market share
of existing markets.

27
00:01:48,641 --> 00:01:49,801
Nothing else matters.

28
00:01:49,876 --> 00:01:51,844
You can talk
about your art history

29
00:01:51,911 --> 00:01:54,277
your Derrida,
your la-dee-dah, your poetry

30
00:01:54,347 --> 00:01:56,781
but in reality,
the moment you step outside

31
00:01:56,850 --> 00:01:59,444
the magic circle drawn
around this institution

32
00:01:59,519 --> 00:02:01,612
you are at the mercy
of market forces

33
00:02:01,688 --> 00:02:04,452
and nowhere will prepare you
more thoroughly to harness

34
00:02:04,524 --> 00:02:06,389
those forces
for your own benefit

35
00:02:06,459 --> 00:02:08,620
than McKinsey
and Company Consulting.

36
00:02:08,695 --> 00:02:11,061
Remember, follow the bouncing
ball to McKinsey.

37
00:02:11,131 --> 00:02:12,894
You got to get
over to l-banking.

38
00:02:12,966 --> 00:02:15,400
You won't buy workout clothes
for ten years.

39
00:02:15,468 --> 00:02:17,868
Somehow l don't see you working
in a bank.

40
00:02:17,937 --> 00:02:19,700
Thanks.

41
00:02:21,274 --> 00:02:24,732
l calculated the odds
of getting hired by McKinsey.

42
00:02:24,811 --> 00:02:27,644
From Stanford or here,
it's about 500 to one.

43
00:02:27,714 --> 00:02:29,944
From anywhere else,
forget about it.

44
00:02:30,049 --> 00:02:32,381
Why do you tell me these things?

45
00:02:55,008 --> 00:02:56,498
So...

46
00:02:56,576 --> 00:02:57,941
how you doing?

47
00:02:58,011 --> 00:03:00,104
l'm fine.

48
00:03:00,180 --> 00:03:02,774
That could be the most dangerous
lie you tell today.

49
00:03:02,849 --> 00:03:05,613
Come on, Bill.
l've been back for ten minutes.

50
00:03:05,685 --> 00:03:07,710
Just put me to work.
l'll be okay.

51
00:03:07,787 --> 00:03:11,780
l've got a Missing Persons.

52
00:03:11,858 --> 00:03:14,326
Male, Caucasian, 24 years.

53
00:03:14,394 --> 00:03:15,759
Name: Embry Larkin.

54
00:03:15,828 --> 00:03:18,160
So, when'd this kid go missing?

55
00:03:18,231 --> 00:03:20,699
Uh... two years ago,
from the university.

56
00:03:20,767 --> 00:03:23,759
Rich kid.
Dropped out. No family.

57
00:03:23,836 --> 00:03:26,066
Some um, lawyer-- a trustee--

58
00:03:26,139 --> 00:03:28,869
says he hasn't touched
his accounts.

59
00:03:28,942 --> 00:03:31,308
Now tell me he was
on drugs and depressed.

60
00:03:31,377 --> 00:03:32,776
Well, there is a drug thing,
yeah.

61
00:03:32,845 --> 00:03:33,777
Come on, Bill.

62
00:03:33,846 --> 00:03:35,040
He drove up north

63
00:03:35,114 --> 00:03:36,877
with a couple of rocks
in his pocket.

64
00:03:36,950 --> 00:03:38,781
-He jumped in a lake.
-Hey, we're not looking

65
00:03:38,851 --> 00:03:40,182
to hit any home runs here, okay?

66
00:03:40,253 --> 00:03:41,413
The kid had money.

67
00:03:41,487 --> 00:03:45,355
lt's going to get investigated
and you're the right guy today.

68
00:03:45,425 --> 00:03:47,290
You going to give me a cruiser?

69
00:03:51,097 --> 00:03:52,223
''Boa. B-O-A.''

70
00:03:52,298 --> 00:03:54,698
My mother's been
to a snake church.

71
00:03:54,767 --> 00:03:56,200
Did you say, ''snake church''?

72
00:03:56,269 --> 00:03:57,668
Yeah, snake church.

73
00:03:57,737 --> 00:04:00,535
Okay. ''Persian religious
teacher.'' Nine letters.

74
00:04:00,607 --> 00:04:01,574
Zoroaster.

75
00:04:01,641 --> 00:04:03,734
Great. Good and evil.

76
00:04:03,810 --> 00:04:05,300
''My book is Genius''--
''Genius'' capitalized.

77
00:04:05,378 --> 00:04:07,243
He's a physicist.
l should know this.

78
00:04:07,313 --> 00:04:08,302
He had weird hair.

79
00:04:08,381 --> 00:04:09,348
''Feynman. F-E...''

80
00:04:09,415 --> 00:04:10,677
l can spell ''Feynman.''

81
00:04:10,750 --> 00:04:11,739
''F-U-C. Feynman.''

82
00:04:11,818 --> 00:04:13,843
l'm sorry.

83
00:04:13,920 --> 00:04:15,649
My McKinsey interview is
in 30 minutes.

84
00:04:15,722 --> 00:04:18,088
Personally, l'm not a dog
that salivates every time

85
00:04:18,157 --> 00:04:20,717
some l-banker consultant
rings his little bell.

86
00:04:20,793 --> 00:04:23,819
Hey, um, Katie, um

87
00:04:23,896 --> 00:04:25,420
l love being friends
in quotation marks.

88
00:04:25,498 --> 00:04:27,796
lt makes me so horny.

89
00:04:30,370 --> 00:04:31,632
Knock it off. We are friends.

90
00:04:31,704 --> 00:04:34,264
Hey, Katie.

91
00:04:34,340 --> 00:04:36,535
Amanda. Sam. August.

92
00:04:36,609 --> 00:04:40,101
So, um, we were just talking
about friendship and how...

93
00:04:40,179 --> 00:04:41,578
How we'll all be selling out.

94
00:04:41,648 --> 00:04:42,580
Sooner or later.

95
00:04:42,649 --> 00:04:43,877
Some of us sooner than others.

96
00:04:43,950 --> 00:04:45,212
l don't know, you guys.

97
00:04:45,285 --> 00:04:47,947
l think it's just really about
doing what makes you happy.

98
00:04:48,021 --> 00:04:52,822
He's right. Harrison,
you're just so... hopeful.

99
00:04:52,892 --> 00:04:54,883
Oh, thanks.

100
00:05:14,080 --> 00:05:15,513
Sorry to keep you waiting.

101
00:05:15,581 --> 00:05:17,412
l already spoke
with two officers.

102
00:05:17,483 --> 00:05:19,576
l'm not sure
what else l can tell you.

103
00:05:19,652 --> 00:05:21,119
Right, right.

104
00:05:21,187 --> 00:05:24,020
Well, those other two detectives
are no longer on this case.

105
00:05:24,090 --> 00:05:25,284
l am.

106
00:05:27,360 --> 00:05:29,351
So, what makes you think
Embry Larkin is dead?

107
00:05:29,429 --> 00:05:30,760
Purely account activity.

108
00:05:30,830 --> 00:05:32,764
We haven't heard from him
in a couple of years.

109
00:05:32,832 --> 00:05:34,356
He hasn't used
any credit facilities.

110
00:05:34,434 --> 00:05:35,833
But this kid was
all over the map.

111
00:05:35,902 --> 00:05:38,166
l mean, how do we know
he's not sitting on some island

112
00:05:38,237 --> 00:05:39,727
smoking Thai stick,
wearing a sheet?

113
00:05:39,806 --> 00:05:41,535
He also had
two first-class airline tickets

114
00:05:41,607 --> 00:05:43,131
to Athens, Greece,
that he never used.

115
00:05:43,209 --> 00:05:44,369
lt takes seven years

116
00:05:44,444 --> 00:05:46,935
for a missing person
to be declared dead.

117
00:05:47,013 --> 00:05:50,312
Now's as good a time as any
to get the ball rolling.

118
00:05:50,383 --> 00:05:51,407
Right.

119
00:05:51,484 --> 00:05:52,678
Well, who gets the money?

120
00:05:52,752 --> 00:05:54,310
The Larkin Foundation.

121
00:05:54,387 --> 00:05:57,151
-All of it?
-All of it.

122
00:05:57,223 --> 00:06:00,715
Look, his family was a client
of the original partners.

123
00:06:00,793 --> 00:06:03,193
l don't know this kid at all.

124
00:07:00,186 --> 00:07:01,414
Katie!

125
00:07:02,922 --> 00:07:04,014
Hi, Katie Burke.

126
00:07:04,090 --> 00:07:06,058
There is a message for you.

127
00:07:06,125 --> 00:07:09,652
Your thesis advisor,
Professor Jergensen's office

128
00:07:09,729 --> 00:07:12,425
they said l should find you,
so l did.

129
00:07:12,498 --> 00:07:15,262
Here's the message.

130
00:07:15,334 --> 00:07:17,894
lt says for you to come
to Jergensen's house.

131
00:07:18,037 --> 00:07:19,129
That's scary.

132
00:07:19,205 --> 00:07:21,070
How's your thesis coming,
anyway?

133
00:07:21,140 --> 00:07:23,370
lt's almost done. How's yours?

134
00:07:23,443 --> 00:07:26,879
Turned it in.

135
00:07:26,946 --> 00:07:29,779
Ms. Burke, l'd like
to have you meet Wade Handler.

136
00:07:29,849 --> 00:07:30,816
He's a police officer.

137
00:07:30,883 --> 00:07:31,815
Hello.

138
00:07:31,884 --> 00:07:33,146
Hi.

139
00:07:33,219 --> 00:07:34,914
Mr. Handler has a line
of inquiries...

140
00:07:34,987 --> 00:07:36,352
That's ''Detective,'' Professor.

141
00:07:36,422 --> 00:07:38,720
''Doctor,'' Detective.

142
00:07:38,791 --> 00:07:40,691
Detective Handler has a line
of inquiry

143
00:07:40,760 --> 00:07:42,193
that he's forcing
upon the college.

144
00:07:42,261 --> 00:07:43,751
Force?
Oh, no, we don't use force--

145
00:07:43,830 --> 00:07:45,889
not in the People's Republic--
we ask politely

146
00:07:45,965 --> 00:07:48,695
because the college is good
for the tax base

147
00:07:48,768 --> 00:07:50,668
which is good
for the community

148
00:07:50,736 --> 00:07:52,499
which is good for everybody.

149
00:07:52,572 --> 00:07:54,233
So, um, Katherine Burke...

150
00:07:54,307 --> 00:07:55,467
Katie.

151
00:07:55,541 --> 00:07:58,510
Katie... l'm investigating
a young man

152
00:07:58,578 --> 00:08:01,411
who was a student here,
Embry Larkin.

153
00:08:01,481 --> 00:08:03,073
Something happen to him?

154
00:08:03,149 --> 00:08:05,879
Well, that's
what l'm trying to find out.

155
00:08:05,985 --> 00:08:07,816
What was your relationship?

156
00:08:07,887 --> 00:08:09,252
He was my boyfriend.

157
00:08:09,322 --> 00:08:13,156
Detective, this college is
very proactive

158
00:08:13,226 --> 00:08:14,989
about the privacy
of its students.

159
00:08:15,061 --> 00:08:16,995
Oh, l understand, Doctor.
l'll be gentle.

160
00:08:18,798 --> 00:08:22,859
So... he was your boyfriend?

161
00:08:22,935 --> 00:08:24,630
He disappeared.

162
00:08:24,704 --> 00:08:26,467
He left school.

163
00:08:26,539 --> 00:08:27,904
He disappeared,
or he left school?

164
00:08:27,974 --> 00:08:28,906
Which?

165
00:08:29,041 --> 00:08:30,269
Both, l think.

166
00:08:30,343 --> 00:08:32,903
l... haven't heard from him.

167
00:08:32,979 --> 00:08:34,503
Not once?

168
00:08:34,580 --> 00:08:36,343
Not even once.

169
00:08:36,415 --> 00:08:37,780
Do you have any idea

170
00:08:37,850 --> 00:08:40,114
-where he might be?
-No.

171
00:08:41,687 --> 00:08:43,655
That's fine.

172
00:08:43,723 --> 00:08:44,917
Thank you for your time.

173
00:08:44,991 --> 00:08:45,923
Here's my card.

174
00:08:46,058 --> 00:08:49,027
lf you think of anything else,
just give me a call, all right?

175
00:08:49,095 --> 00:08:51,086
How's your thesis coming?

176
00:08:51,163 --> 00:08:52,596
l'm learning so much.

177
00:08:52,665 --> 00:08:54,360
You have a draft for me?

178
00:08:54,433 --> 00:08:55,923
Close, really close.

179
00:08:56,068 --> 00:08:57,899
Let's preserve our older dorms.

180
00:08:57,970 --> 00:08:59,403
Go home, leave it alone.

181
00:08:59,472 --> 00:09:01,374
Let's preserve our older dorms.

182
00:09:01,440 --> 00:09:03,101
Go home, leave it alone.

183
00:09:03,175 --> 00:09:05,143
Let's preserve
our older dorms...

184
00:10:09,976 --> 00:10:11,944
How'd it go?

185
00:10:14,046 --> 00:10:17,174
l completely blew it.

186
00:10:17,249 --> 00:10:19,809
There's tea and stale pastries.

187
00:10:19,885 --> 00:10:23,082
Don't, whatever you do,
take one.

188
00:10:23,155 --> 00:10:26,522
l got crumbs
all over my cashmere sweater.

189
00:10:26,592 --> 00:10:28,685
l won't be wearing
a cashmere sweater.

190
00:10:28,761 --> 00:10:30,956
So, l don't think
that'll be a problem.

191
00:10:31,030 --> 00:10:33,624
Ooh, working-class hero,
good strategy.

192
00:10:33,699 --> 00:10:34,961
They hated me.

193
00:10:35,034 --> 00:10:35,966
l could tell.

194
00:10:36,035 --> 00:10:39,095
They want Vietnamese orphans...
and engineers.

195
00:10:39,171 --> 00:10:41,469
God, why wasn't I born
a Vietnamese orphan?

196
00:10:41,540 --> 00:10:42,871
This is so familiar--

197
00:10:42,942 --> 00:10:46,070
''l blew it. l'm a loser,'' and
then, ''Oh, look, l got an A.''

198
00:10:46,145 --> 00:10:47,112
No.

199
00:10:47,179 --> 00:10:49,477
l lost my concentration.

200
00:10:49,548 --> 00:10:50,981
l wasn't supposed
to concentrate.

201
00:10:51,117 --> 00:10:52,607
lt was supposed
to be effortless.

202
00:10:52,685 --> 00:10:54,983
And then,
l started concentrating

203
00:10:55,121 --> 00:10:56,611
and becoming earnest

204
00:10:56,689 --> 00:10:59,624
and then l started seeing them
as seeing me as seeing myself

205
00:10:59,692 --> 00:11:02,092
as the type of person who wants
to appear earnest

206
00:11:02,161 --> 00:11:03,458
which is completely wro...

207
00:11:03,529 --> 00:11:06,464
Do you hear what's going on
up here?

208
00:11:06,532 --> 00:11:09,296
l hate wearing
these itchy things.

209
00:11:09,368 --> 00:11:10,926
How do l look?

210
00:11:11,037 --> 00:11:13,267
How do you think you look?

211
00:11:13,339 --> 00:11:15,273
...Of unbounded domesticity

212
00:11:15,341 --> 00:11:17,935
Though a doctor of divinity
is located in this vicinity

213
00:11:18,044 --> 00:11:21,377
But they give up the felicity
of unbounded domesticity

214
00:11:21,447 --> 00:11:23,847
Though a doctor of divinity

215
00:11:23,916 --> 00:11:25,406
A doctor of divinity...

216
00:11:25,484 --> 00:11:29,477
Headline: ''Composer
of Questionable Talent

217
00:11:29,555 --> 00:11:33,958
''Excoriates Audience
For Enjoying His Music.

218
00:11:34,026 --> 00:11:36,358
''ln a bizarre exercise
in self-loathing

219
00:11:36,429 --> 00:11:37,896
''Senior Embry Larkin--

220
00:11:37,963 --> 00:11:41,831
''winner of the Leonard Bernstein
Award for Original Composition--

221
00:11:41,901 --> 00:11:45,530
''stood up before his
latest theatrical production

222
00:11:45,604 --> 00:11:49,973
Trip-Hop Inferno

223
00:11:50,042 --> 00:11:54,706
and lacerated the audience
for their attendance.''

224
00:11:56,782 --> 00:11:59,148
He flipped off 200 people

225
00:11:59,218 --> 00:12:02,153
and disappeared three weeks
before graduation.

226
00:12:02,221 --> 00:12:04,086
He was already
Summa Cum Laude

227
00:12:04,156 --> 00:12:06,750
and he says,
''Screw you and your degree.''

228
00:12:06,826 --> 00:12:11,525
lt was exceedingly theatrical
and standard Embry.

229
00:12:11,597 --> 00:12:12,928
What was standard about it?

230
00:12:12,998 --> 00:12:14,329
Dropped out twice--

231
00:12:14,400 --> 00:12:19,167
once to work on some
archeological dig in Cambodia...

232
00:12:19,238 --> 00:12:21,570
once to work in a factory.

233
00:12:21,640 --> 00:12:25,132
l expect him to pop up
running La Scala

234
00:12:25,211 --> 00:12:26,940
or the Berlin Opera.

235
00:12:27,079 --> 00:12:28,171
What a guy.

236
00:12:30,583 --> 00:12:31,948
800 math S.A.T.s.

237
00:12:32,017 --> 00:12:32,949
3.94 GPA.

238
00:12:33,018 --> 00:12:34,508
Thesis?

239
00:12:34,587 --> 00:12:38,182
''Emerging Ancillary Markets in
the Global Wireless Revolution.''

240
00:12:38,257 --> 00:12:39,724
l bet that's quite a read.

241
00:12:39,792 --> 00:12:42,727
We're actually looking
to beef up our Tech Practice

242
00:12:42,795 --> 00:12:45,093
but then you probably
already knew that.

243
00:12:45,164 --> 00:12:47,496
So...

244
00:12:47,566 --> 00:12:48,794
''Katherine Burke...''

245
00:12:48,868 --> 00:12:49,857
who are you?

246
00:12:49,935 --> 00:12:51,926
Where do you come from?

247
00:12:52,004 --> 00:12:53,801
l grew up
in the middle of nowhere.

248
00:12:53,873 --> 00:12:55,568
The birthplace
of Wendell Willkie

249
00:12:55,641 --> 00:12:57,609
is 20 miles away,
and that's about it.

250
00:12:57,676 --> 00:13:01,009
My mom works in a bottling plant
and sells Nutra-Life products

251
00:13:01,080 --> 00:13:03,105
and my dad left
when l was little.

252
00:13:03,182 --> 00:13:04,672
l never really knew him.

253
00:13:04,750 --> 00:13:07,275
Hmm.

254
00:13:10,022 --> 00:13:12,286
Tell us about a problem
you've encountered.

255
00:13:12,358 --> 00:13:13,825
My guidance counselor tried

256
00:13:13,893 --> 00:13:16,123
to keep me from applying
to good schools.

257
00:13:16,195 --> 00:13:17,719
l thought she was my friend.

258
00:13:17,797 --> 00:13:19,230
She said she understood me

259
00:13:19,298 --> 00:13:22,096
and that l would be happier
staying close to home--

260
00:13:22,168 --> 00:13:24,159
junior college
or secretarial school.

261
00:13:24,236 --> 00:13:25,464
She hated me.

262
00:13:25,538 --> 00:13:27,096
What action did you take?

263
00:13:27,173 --> 00:13:29,573
l invited a senator
